## Implementation Plan: Extracting Business Logic into a Service Layer

### 1. Error Handling Strategy: Custom Error Classes

I recommend **custom error classes** over result objects for several reasons specific to this codebase:

**Why custom errors over result objects:**

- The route handlers currently use early-return patterns with different HTTP status codes (400, 404). Custom error classes map cleanly to this: throw from the service, catch in the handler, map class to status code.
- Result objects (e.g., `{ ok: true, data } | { ok: false, error }`) would require the route handler to check discriminated unions at every service call site, adding boilerplate that defeats the "thin handler" goal.
- TypeScript strict mode benefits from thrown errors because the service function return type only describes the success case -- no union with error variants cluttering the type.
- The existing tests check exact error message strings (e.g., `"Product not found"`, `"Insufficient stock"`, `"Cannot transition from X to Y"`). Custom error classes can carry those messages directly.

**Error class design -- add to `src/types.ts`:**

```typescript
export class ServiceError extends Error {
  constructor(
    message: string,
    public readonly statusCode: number
  ) {
    super(message);
    this.name = "ServiceError";
  }
}

export class NotFoundError extends ServiceError {
  constructor(message: string) {
    super(message, 404);
    this.name = "NotFoundError";
  }
}

export class ValidationError extends ServiceError {
  constructor(message: string) {
    super(message, 400);
    this.name = "ValidationError";
  }
}
```

Three classes, one base and two specific. The base class carries `statusCode` so the route handler catch block only needs: `if (e instanceof ServiceError) { res.status(e.statusCode).json({ error: e.message }); }`. The two subclasses (`NotFoundError`, `ValidationError`) give semantic meaning and map precisely to the two HTTP error codes used in the existing handlers (400 and 404).

No other status codes are needed -- the codebase only uses 200, 201, 400, and 404.

